What will you do with the time you have on this earth? When’s the last time that you stopped to feel the wind in your face; the last time you told someone you loved them. The world is falling apart. Good friends, good memories, good whiskey. There’s a lot of small things to notice. Take the time to appreciate them.
I have hope for you.

As a New York model agent you see so many celebrities come in and out of your life. Recording artist Brandon aka B Smyth was always a great soul to be around. He had great manners, always so polite and would get dancing in the agency as he played us new songs. We loved having him as a model with us. When he passed at such a young age this year due to pulmonary fibrosis it reminded me once again how fragile life is. We have to take the time we have while we’re here to chase our dreams, say what we need to say, scream out loud, take the time to really consider what happiness is to us and really whether that happiness is for us or simply makes us feel or look more important to others. Take a moment for this, because it’s Christmas isn’t it? At the end of the year you serve yourself to reflect on what you’re grateful for or how you can be better to others around you. The best way to celebrate the holidays is to celebrate your life and the others around you. #Happyholidays #ripbsmyth #rememberingbsmyth #bsmyth

Tatjana Patitz was one of the models I used to see in every issue of Top Model Magazine in the 90’s. She had these wolf eyes that I was so magnetized by. Tatjana was one of the models that made me want to be in fashion. While her fellow supermodels pushed the ceiling higher she chose to settle in California to a life closer to her soul. We have missed her in the industry but it’s extraordinary how the work she did so long ago lasts forever. RIP #TatjanaPatitz.  #gregchaninspirations

It makes me happy to see so many people recognize the love that Jeremy Ruehlemann brought to the world. Like every fucking person he came across. His energy was so beautiful. Sometimes when you spread good energy to others, you don’t really know if anyone notices or if anyone really cares at all. Jeremy we noticed. Jeremy just did it. He did it freely and genuinely. We can also tend to judge people by appearances, people that have bleached hair or a body covered in tattoos. Jeremy had the ability to disarm anyone that came to him with judgment…with just his smile. Everyone loved his energy. His clients loved his energy. I loved your energy Jeremy. And I’m heartbroken to lose you as a friend. There’s so much love here for you my man. I will miss you.  #jeremyruehlemann

I couldn’t help but smile the entire time watching the “Shalom Harlow’s Life in Looks” in @voguemagazine. Being a bright eyed young model agent in the 90’s New York City was one of the most extraordinary experiences of my life, feverishly pursuing something that I wasn’t exactly sure what it was. I just knew I wanted to be there. I was in awe backstage at shows watching models like Shalom, Amber, Kate, Naomi, Stephanie Seymour…the cool new wave of girls like Kristen McMenamy, Kirsten Owen, Tanga, Stella, Esther Canadas, Alek Wek… Shalom is right, Todd Oldham was a SCENE, it was such a fucking scene. The presence of these models had such a power over me. That kind of power influences me today as an agent on how I want my own talent to make an impact and wish the business still allowed them to fully wield it. I am grateful and in admiration of the agents from that time still around that understand what what possible, what is was like to manage these models, what you were actually creating…knowing that these agents like me understand what these massive careers were truly like.  Back then not everyone could call themselves a supermodels like they do today. Artists deep in artists.  These stories are worth fucking gold.  #90smodels #90smodelsrule #supermodel

I’ve been talking to a lot of people lately telling me about their fears, anxiety & low self esteem they live thru every day. You’re not alone. The world is a terrifying place of judgement. We have to stop thinking that success or acknowledgement from others will make everything right. Belief in yourself starts with you and it’s a life long process. I’m chasing it still too. But we can make a difference in our own lives whether it’s pursuing the life we want no matter if we win or lose or standing ground to our authentic selves, not afraid of being you in front of others. It’s a great time in the world to double down on you & start swinging for the fences. Don’t stop the chase. This is the way it’s supposed to be. Just try to do with with curiosity and excitement rather than letting the weight get heavier. Put on your favorite song right now. Ask someone out in a date. Make pancakes for dinner. Stand on a chair and look down on the world being a little higher than before. This is your life. You are perfect. If you need someone to give you a boost. Send me a DM.

Today I found out I lost a friend. Peter Vancek was my hairdresser for 25 years. I had been texting him the past couple years to no response. I wondered if he was mad at me & I even texted him asking him if I had done anything to upset him. I hadn’t needed his services as a hairdresser in yrs as I had grown out my hair long to donate it, then when he cut it all off, I used a clipper. But it wasn’t in his nature to take things personally. He was a people person. I woke up this am thinking about him & decided to call. The number was out of order. He would die with that number. His last IG post was 2021. My gut told me to google him & my fears slowly unfolded into choked breathing. He had passed 2 years ago.  I have lived my life long enough to grow up w people in this city, long enough to start losing friends. The worst thing is not knowing you could have been there for someone you care about. It’s the FUCKING worst. Not knowing you could have checked in more often to say “hey are you ok?” I remember the last time he called me I didn’t pick up. I was too pre-occupied w my own shit. Then I forgot. That was right about that time. Reach out to people to tell them you love them. Ask you’re friends if they’re ok. Our moments with each other are shorter than we think. I’m so sorry Peter. This guy was a great hairdresser. He worked at the best but he chose to work rogue always cutting peoples hair on the side. I would send all of my modes & celebs to him. He would go to your house white glove & cut your hair. I would find out later against my wishes the reason why everyone loved him was not for his cuts but bc he would roll a joint with them after. The models fucking loved him.  He was a true hustler. The 1st time I met him he came up to my friend Brian at 2am at Wax club in the 90’s and offered to cut our hair. We thought he was trying to pick us up. He became a friend for life. A true New York hustler. Cash only always. He had the gift of the gab. Always “knew a guy” for everything. You don’t make ‘em like this anymore. You’re a dear dear friend Peter. I love you brother & will miss you so much. Thank you for our memories together.

BREAKING NEWS: Bombshell update; the shelter ended up rejecting the applicant due to inaccurate past pet records. Didn’t see that coming but it shows how much this shelter cares. Looks like Tommy is still with me for a bit! I got the call from the shelter that someone is interested in adopting Tommy. When you foster an animal for an extended time there is a period of time when you try not to get too close and another point in time where you get so attached. And it is heartbreaking. I’ve spent 2 years rehabbing Tommy, the longest I’ve ever spent fostering an animal and watched him grow from a terrified & traumatized cat to a beautifully loving creature. I’m able to give a gift in this world which is to save a life. I can’t go into the reasons why I’m unable to keep Tommy but it has been an emotional day for me. We screen pretty rigidly at the shelter and I think this guy might be the one. The thing I can do is to know I found a beautiful furr-ever home where he will be loved the rest of his life. It’s special. So everyone wish Tommy luck. And here’s to 2nd chances. ❤️

Saying goodbye to this great man. This is Dr. James Graves who was a great mystic, spiritual practitioner, energy mover. He studied and worked with Sai Baba in India, the Dalai Lama, the majestic Oracle of Tibet. I studied with him in a metaphysical group back in the early 2000’s. In 2004 I got a chance to go on a spiritual mission with him to Egypt where we travelled the Nile river, visited the great pyramid of Giza, visited St. Catherine’s Monastery in the Sinai desert, the 3rd holiest place on the planet where we had a personal audience with the High Cardinal there, bathed in the electric Red Sea. We climbed Mt. Sinai by camel caravan and by foot and celebrated his 73rd birthday up there. Dr. Graves was also an esteemed UFO researcher and would spend late nights showing me his research, interviews and videos. But the greatest thing he taught me was in his final weeks sitting beside him at the hospital. He was fiery & colorful until the end. No compromise. He knew who he was. I would call his wife while I was there and let them speak to each other on speaker. I would sit there for an hour while they just professed their love for each other over and over again. “Youre my precious. You’re my dream come true.” These are the things to live for. Identify what’s really important while we’re here on this planet. Thank you Dr. Graves and farewell for now my friend.

I started the 1st couple days of the year frustrated, I made a couple financial mistakes and was really beating myself up. Then I realized I have the whole rest of the year to kick ass. Looking back at the changes I’ve made in my life & the impact I’m making, I’m receiving my certification for next level. Practice acceptance & lean into the process. The excitement & ambition of new year energy is just too big. I’ve got strength & courage & ideas. I’ve just discovered my favorite new “fist in the air” rock band to crank up in the car. And this weekend I’m going to hike a mountain and yell as loud as I can at the edge. Take a moment to look how far you’ve come. The path is there before you. Goodbye 2023 hello future.
